 So we'll start out, say, with comments.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:09.720
 So I love the comments in JavaScript.

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:14.640
 There are two kinds of comments, and they have to do with what languages did the influencing.

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:20.120
 And so the slash star, star slash, is a multi-line comment, right?

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:25.640
 So this is all comment from here all the way to here, and you can have new lines.

00:00:25.640 --> 00:00:27.920
 This is great for writing documentation.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:30.080
 That comes from the C language.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.040
 Java also supports it as well.

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:36.800
 And then the C++ language has slash slash to the end of the line.

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:40.600
 Well, that's much more like the pound sign comment in Python.

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:43.000
 But I like both of those styles.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.520
 I like using these for documentation sections, and I like these for short comments.

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:48.960
 So nice.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:50.240
 Thank you very much.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:53.680
 White space and new lines do not matter.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:58.640
 Statements end in a semicolon, it turns out that that's not technically true.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:03.600
 But if you just pretend that all statements end in a semicolon, then if you move to Java

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:10.400
 or C++ or C or PHP, then you're not like, oh, when do I have to put the semicolon on?

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:12.520
 Well, in those languages, you have to put it on just about everywhere.

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:17.720
 So just put semicolons at the end of every line, and you can just pretend you're writing C.

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.720
 And then when you get to C, you'll be like, oh, this is just like JavaScript, even though

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:25.800
 under the implementation, it's very different, very, very different.

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:32.080
 So here is just an example of some really nasty JavaScript where x equals three plus

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:37.320
 five times four on two lines, and then this line's jammed up, and console.log.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:38.320
 That's okay.

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:40.320
 It just doesn't matter.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:45.600
 JavaScript and these C-style languages just don't care what the white space is.

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:50.680
 They're looking for characters, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:54.400
 Semicolon, that must be the end of the line, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, semicolon.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:55.560
 That's the end of the line.

00:01:55.560 --> 00:02:04.800
 So just, the new line is just like another space-like character ultimately in these languages.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:07.520
 Variable names are kind of normal.

00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:09.480
 They can start with letters.

00:02:09.480 --> 00:02:15.560
 I mean, they're letters and numbers and underscore and dollar sign, but they're not supposed

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.320
 to start with a number, and they are case sensitive.

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:19.660
 Just please.

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:24.280
 We use case sometimes as a signal because different kinds of variables, we like either

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:28.040
 camel case them or all uppercase.

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:39.040
 I use case to signal things, and it turns out that because JavaScript sort of saw what

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:44.040
 PHP and Perl looked like, they allowed dollar signs at the beginning variables because PHP

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:47.400
 and Perl are the places where dollar signs are allowed.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:53.480
 But when people started writing JavaScript, they wanted to be more like Java.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:58.000
 Java doesn't allow dollar signs in variables, and so there was kind of like this unwritten

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:03.640
 rule, which we will come back to, of just don't start a variable with dollar sign, even

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:05.240
 though JavaScript allows it.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:06.240
 Just kind of don't do it.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:08.320
 It's not cool.

