00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:36.060
 Unumeric constants are pretty much like every other language, but, but, there is only one

00:04:36.060 --> 00:04:37.240
 number type.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:41.760
 In most languages, there's like an integer and a floating point.

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:43.600
 Sometimes there's double and float.

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.880
 There's different kinds of long integers.

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:52.720
 In JavaScript, I think in a way they were smart, and they basically made one type, one

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:55.160
 numeric type called number.

00:04:55.160 --> 00:05:00.960
 And so for example, if you take five thirds, that is a floating point number, 1.666, repeating

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:01.960
 forever.

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:07.500
 If you want to turn that into an integer, you just truncate it, like math.trunc.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:10.080
 Math is a library that's in JavaScript.

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:14.120
 Now when you get back in X, it's still a floating point number.

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:18.740
 It just is shown as an integer because you've chopped off the decimal part.

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:23.440
 And so you have to be careful because they're really floating point numbers.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:27.440
 Every one of them, some of them are shown as integers when you print them out.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:32.380
 But in general, there are no integers in JavaScript.

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:40.080
 So there's a whole bunch of operators, plus, minus, multiply, divide, truncate, you know,

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:45.560
 those are pretty much like every other programming language.

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:49.240
 More operators like the modulo operator.

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:53.940
 Modulo operator is the percent sign, and that is the remainder operator.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:59.880
 So 45 divided by 7 is 6 remainder 3.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:09.680
 And that remainder, you know, 45, 7 is 6, 42, 3, remainder 3.

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:12.680
 That 3 is what goes there.

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:18.560
 So division with truncation will give you the 6, but the remainder will give you the

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:19.640
 3.

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:22.600
 And it turns out that that modulo is really quite useful.

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:29.360
 Like if you want to do something every hundredth time through an iteration, you take the iteration

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:31.000
 counter like 1, 2, 3.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:36.720
 And if you modulo 100 and the result is 0, remainder 0, it's an even multiple of 100.

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:38.740
 And that means every 100 times you can do something.

00:06:38.740 --> 00:06:42.680
 So we like modulo.

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:45.800
 There are side effect operators.

00:06:45.800 --> 00:06:47.600
 Oops, come back.

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:54.160
 There are side effect operators, k++ says retrieve k, have it be part of an expression

