 perhaps, and then add one to it, store it back down.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:02.680
 So if I say k++, it says 3, but then afterwards k has become 4.

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:07.280
 So after it retrieved the k and printed it, then it turned it into 4.

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:11.420
 These are, there's a very few places that we actually use these, and then we use them

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:17.360
 all the time, but in general, you can hurt yourself if you write too much of this stuff.

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:24.760
 There is a pre-increment, minus, minus k, and that says subtract 1 from k, and then print

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:27.880
 it out, which is 3, and then the 3 goes back into k.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:35.840
 Okay, then there are some side effect operators, j is equal to, j plus equals is the same as

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:41.040
 j equals j plus 5, and the same is true for all these things.

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:47.880
 Actually, this is just, that's a typo there, slash equals.

