 I always prefer to write my increments and decrements and divisions out.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:04.320
 It's not particularly faster that way, it's just, it's a syntax.

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:10.120
 This comes from C, all of these fancy bits come from the C language, and JavaScript was

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:17.760
 just, and Java do the same thing, and so those two languages are represented here, and so

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.440
 that's why these operators are here.

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:26.720
 Comparison operators, all C-style languages, one of the trickiest things you gotta realize

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:31.240
 is that the single equal sign is an assignment statement, and I like to think of that as

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:35.540
 changing, so the 10 is being stored into the j.

00:08:35.540 --> 00:08:37.280
 To say, is j equal to 10?

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:42.920
 This is like a question mark, I wish this was like, question equals, that would be like,

00:08:42.920 --> 00:08:45.480
 is it equal to, but that's not what they do.

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.320
 They decided double equals was the one that was the question mark, and that's asking the

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:54.060
 question is j equal to 10, and it returns a true or a false when it's evaluated.

00:08:54.060 --> 00:09:00.840
 So j equals 10 is true, j not equals 17, that's exclamation equal, again I wish this was question

